1
00:00:03,347 --> 00:00:05,994
[Guest] undeclared wars are commonplace.

2
00:00:05,994 --> 00:00:14,397
Tragically, our government engages in preemptive war otherwise known as aggression with no complaints from the American people.

3
00:00:14,798 --> 00:00:20,977
[Guest] Sadly, we have become accustomed to living with the illegitimate use of force by government.

4
00:00:20,977 --> 00:00:26,847
To develop a truly free society, the issue of initiating force must be understood and rejected.

5
00:00:28,019 --> 00:00:33,020
[Guest] What if sometimes to love your country you had to alter or abolish the government?

6
00:00:33,020 --> 00:00:37,520
What if Jefferson was right? What if that government is best which governs least?

7
00:00:38,719 --> 00:00:43,031
[Guest] What if it is dangerous to be right when the government is wrong?

8
00:00:43,031 --> 00:00:47,520
What if it is better to perish fighting for freedom than to live as a slave?

9
00:00:48,619 --> 00:00:52,520
[Guest] What if freedom's greatest hour of danger is now?

10
00:01:02,643 --> 00:01:07,743
[Host] Hi, everyone. Judge Andrew Napolitano here for Judging Freedom.

11
00:01:07,743 --> 00:01:10,293
Today is Tuesday, April 28th, 2026.

12
00:01:11,343 --> 00:01:15,772
[Host] Professor John Mearsheimer will be with us in just a moment.

13
00:01:15,772 --> 00:01:19,144
Just how did Donald Trump lose his war of choosing?

14
00:01:20,531 --> 00:01:21,531
[Host] But first this.

15
00:01:21,531 --> 00:01:25,652
[Host] Don't you just cringe when people say, I told you so.

16
00:01:25,652 --> 00:01:34,168
Sorry, I told you gold and silver would reap the benefits due to excessive money printing, inflation and global uncertainty.

17
00:01:34,168 --> 00:01:38,631
It's here. It's happened. Gold and silver reached all time highs.

18
00:01:38,731 --> 00:01:43,096
[Host] Did you call Lear Capital and buy some? It's not too late.

19
00:01:43,096 --> 00:01:47,729
Experts are predicting higher prices ahead. Why? Nothing has changed.

20
00:01:47,729 --> 00:01:55,652
Geopolitical chaos, cost of living crises, and a weaker dollar are driving central banks to boost their gold reserves.

21
00:01:56,201 --> 00:02:02,236
[Host] Forecasts suggest gold could hit $6,000 an ounce and silver $200 an ounce.

22
00:02:02,236 --> 00:02:08,940
Even Morgan Stanley ditched the 60-40 rule for 60-20-20, putting 20% into precious metals.

23
00:02:08,940 --> 00:02:14,602
They're getting educated, and you should too. Call the best in the business.

24
00:02:14,548 --> 00:02:17,906
[Host] As in the people I trust, Lear Capital.

25
00:02:17,906 --> 00:02:22,213
Get their reports, get the facts, get some gold and silver.

26
00:02:22,213 --> 00:02:27,689
Tell them the judge sent you and get up to $20,000 in bonus gold or silver.

27
00:02:27,689 --> 00:02:31,048
Call 800-511-4620 or go to leargjudgenap. com.

28
00:02:32,298 --> 00:02:35,847
[Host] Professor Mearsheimer, welcome here, my dear friend.

29
00:02:35,847 --> 00:02:39,997
As always, thank you for accommodating the schedule. How significant?

30
00:02:40,915 --> 00:02:52,265
[Host] In your view, is the trip by Iranian Foreign Minister Arachi to Moscow where he was personally and rather ostentatiously greeted by President Putin himself?

31
00:02:53,460 --> 00:02:59,718
[Guest] Well, I think it has implications beyond the Iran war, and it has implications for U.

32
00:02:59,718 --> 00:03:04,362
S. -Russian relations and for what's going on with regard to Ukraine.

33
00:03:04,362 --> 00:03:09,409
I think if you listen carefully to what the Russians are saying these days,

34
00:03:09,509 --> 00:03:17,000
[Guest] and especially a speech that Lavrov gave on April 24th, you see that the Russians have basically given up on the Americans.

35
00:03:17,000 --> 00:03:19,860
They understand that they're at war with the West.

36
00:03:20,500 --> 00:03:30,066
[Guest] Nothing has changed despite all President Trump's promises of settling the Ukraine war and improving relations between the United States and Russia.

37
00:03:30,066 --> 00:03:34,849
That really hasn't happened. And we still have our gun sights on the Russians.

38
00:03:35,150 --> 00:03:40,622
[Guest] And that's driven the Russians and the Iranians close together.

39
00:03:40,622 --> 00:03:44,322
And I think what you see when Arachi goes to St.

40
00:03:44,521 --> 00:03:55,336
[Guest] Petersburg to talk to Putin and they have this long discussion is evidence of that tight relationship that has developed between the two sides.

41
00:03:55,336 --> 00:04:03,072
And I would note very importantly that there's all sorts of evidence that the Russians are helping Iranians.

42
00:04:04,211 --> 00:04:09,657
[Guest] With their use of drones and ballistic missiles against U. S.

43
00:04:09,657 --> 00:04:12,262
, Israeli, and Gulf State forces,

44
00:04:12,461 --> 00:04:30,482
[Guest] it's quite clear that the Russians are providing satellite data and they're also providing computer chips for the drones and the missiles that work with that satellite data to make Iran's drones and missiles deadly accurate.

45
00:04:30,482 --> 00:04:33,512
So we are up against a very formidable.

46
00:04:33,651 --> 00:04:46,752
[Guest] double fighting force in the Gulf in good part because the Russians are supporting the Iranians and again the Iranians and the Russians have been driven together there's hardly any daylight between them these

47
00:04:46,752 --> 00:04:46,851
[Host] Right.

48
00:04:46,851 --> 00:04:51,901
[Guest] days there's our policies vis-a-vis not only the Russians but the Iranians as well

49
00:04:52,502 --> 00:04:59,552
[Host] So these photos that we're watching or the videos that we're watching, there's...

50
00:05:00,000 --> 00:05:06,417
[Host] Foreign Minister's Rodger and Lavrov and recognized President Putin.

51
00:05:06,417 --> 00:05:12,750
Is this performative or substantive that Putin himself would get involved?

52
00:05:14,163 --> 00:05:17,296
[Guest] Though it's definitely substantive.

53
00:05:17,296 --> 00:05:20,065
I mean, this is high stakes diplomacy.

54
00:05:20,065 --> 00:05:24,363
I mean, this really involves issues that matter enormously.

55
00:05:24,663 --> 00:05:38,318
[Guest] What I find very interesting in addition to the substance is just how optimistic or cheerful the Russians and the Iranians appear.

56
00:05:38,318 --> 00:05:42,176
I think in both cases, they understand.

57
00:05:42,176 --> 00:05:46,925
And they have the Americans on their back heels,

58
00:05:47,076 --> 00:05:58,992
[Guest] that we're in deep trouble in the Middle East and we're in deep trouble in Ukraine and that they are in many ways in the driver's seat.

59
00:05:58,992 --> 00:06:02,826
So you don't see any evidence of deep concern,

60
00:06:02,975 --> 00:06:08,826
[Guest] of pessimism on the part of either one of those two leaders in the video that you're showing.

61
00:06:09,300 --> 00:06:11,149
[Host] Right. Right.

62
00:06:12,600 --> 00:06:14,699
[Guest] The Iranians have.

63
00:06:15,891 --> 00:06:37,164
[Host] reiterated to the americans apparently in whatever the most recent communication was whether it was direct or through the pakistanis i don't know their steadfast and consistent position that they will not voluntarily give up on the right to enrich uranium for civilian purposes does the u.

64
00:06:37,164 --> 00:06:42,841
s take this seriously do they recognize that other countries have red lines you

65
00:06:42,612 --> 00:06:43,562
[Host] Minds just like we do.

66
00:06:44,711 --> 00:06:51,139
[Guest] Well, the United States is not very good at accepting the idea that other countries have red lines.

67
00:06:51,139 --> 00:06:53,362
We think it's our way or the highway.

68
00:06:54,862 --> 00:06:59,652
[Guest] That's certainly been the case on the nuclear enrichment issue.

69
00:06:59,652 --> 00:07:04,172
We were forced to compromise somewhat on that issue with the JCPOA.

70
00:07:04,172 --> 00:07:11,661
The Israelis didn't like that, and they, I think, convinced Trump that the JCPOA was therefore a bad agreement.

71
00:07:11,668 --> 00:07:29,161
[Guest] agreement that he of course pulled out of it in 2018 but I think what's most interesting here is that What the Americans want to do is they want to start by negotiating on the nuclear issue, the nuclear enrichment issue, as you put it.

72
00:07:30,062 --> 00:07:41,128
[Guest] But with the latest proposal that's come out of Iran, they've moved the nuclear enrichment table to number three on the list of issues that have to be dealt with.

73
00:07:41,128 --> 00:07:46,661
They say that first of all, what we have to do is we have to have a meaningful peace.

74
00:07:47,124 --> 00:07:56,046
[Guest] We have to shut down this conflict, and there has to be some guarantee that the United States and Israel are not going to attack Iran again.

75
00:07:56,046 --> 00:07:57,493
That's the first demand.

76
00:07:57,493 --> 00:08:01,774
The second demand is that they'll then talk about the Strait of Hormuz.

77
00:08:01,973 --> 00:08:10,727
[Guest] And of course, it's very clear that they are going to maintain control of the Strait of Hormuz for as far as the eye can see.

78
00:08:10,727 --> 00:08:14,873
So they're not going to make any concessions to us on that one.

79
00:08:14,873 --> 00:08:17,439
And then number three, they'll be able,

80
00:08:17,540 --> 00:08:20,863
[Guest] they'll be willing to talk about the nuclear issue.

81
00:08:20,863 --> 00:08:29,312
So in other words, you have to basically shut down the conflict, then deal with the issue of the strait, and then we can talk about the nuclear issue.

82
00:08:29,312 --> 00:08:31,339
This is not what the Americans want.

83
00:08:31,439 --> 00:08:35,312
[Guest] The Americans want that nuclear issue front and center.

84
00:08:35,312 --> 00:08:42,442
But all of this shows you that as time goes by, the Iranians feel more and more more confident about their position.

85
00:08:42,442 --> 00:08:46,192
This gets back to my earlier point about the smiling faces in

86
00:08:46,192 --> 00:08:46,491
[Host] Right

87
00:08:46,491 --> 00:08:48,417
[Guest] St. Petersburg.

88
00:08:48,417 --> 00:08:53,858
And as I've said many times on this show, time is on Iran's side.

89
00:08:53,858 --> 00:08:58,462
There's no rush, in my opinion, for Iran to cut a deal.

90
00:08:58,462 --> 00:09:04,991
Just let time go by and let the economic consequences of this war take effect.

91
00:09:05,192 --> 00:09:09,681
[Guest] And that will put greater and greater pressure on the Americans.

92
00:09:09,681 --> 00:09:13,546
Americans settle, and that'll give the Iranians more leverage.

93
00:09:13,546 --> 00:09:20,841
So what you see happening here is with this new three-point plan, the Iranians are actually driving a harder bargain.

94
00:09:20,892 --> 00:09:32,491
[Guest] And of course, President Trump is deeply dissatisfied with this new three-point proposal that the Iranians have put forward because, as I said, he wants to get the nuclear issue settled first.

95
00:09:33,427 --> 00:09:41,477
[Host] Here's Foreign Minister Arachi yesterday thanking the Russians, cut number 12.

96
00:09:42,427 --> 00:09:58,778
[Host] As you noted, the entire world, it was proven to the entire world that the Iranian people, with their courage, with their resistance against the American onslaught, against the American aggression, will...

97
00:10:00,000 --> 00:10:04,600
[Host] withstand these trials this period of time.

98
00:10:05,250 --> 00:10:24,649
[Host] And also it was proven to everybody that Tehran has friends and allies such as Russia that in the times of need are standing next to Iran and we are grateful to you for your support and of the Islamic Republic of Iran.

99
00:10:27,539 --> 00:10:36,690
[Guest] Well, a decent statement and one that you would expect he would make publicly towards the end of their meeting.

100
00:10:38,940 --> 00:10:47,005
[Guest] On Sunday, Foreign Minister or Foreign Minister, forgive me, Secretary of State Rubio made some comments that I thought were irrational.

101
00:10:47,005 --> 00:10:49,190
It was odd for him to be talking about.

102
00:10:51,059 --> 00:10:54,144
[Guest] negotiations with Iran is totally out of the picture.

103
00:10:54,144 --> 00:10:55,559
He hasn't been in Islamabad.

104
00:10:55,960 --> 00:11:08,960
[Guest] As far as we know, he doesn't participate in any of the negotiations, unlike all of his predecessors who'd be front and center because the president has chosen his two allies and his son-in-law and his former business partner.

105
00:11:09,610 --> 00:11:12,742
[Guest] But tell me what you think of this.

106
00:11:12,742 --> 00:11:18,059
Vice President Rubio about the Strait of Hormuz on Sunday, cut number 10.

107
00:11:19,091 --> 00:11:27,893
[Host] On Saturday, the President canceled the talks in Islamabad, Pakistan, keeping special envoys Kushner and Whitkoff here in the United States.

108
00:11:27,893 --> 00:11:33,221
He said just ten minutes later the Iranians made a new offer on paper, and it was better.

109
00:11:33,221 --> 00:11:42,337
[Host] If what they mean by opening the straits is, yes, the straits are open as long as you coordinate with Iran, get our permission or we'll blow you up and you pay us, that's not opening the straits.

110
00:11:42,337 --> 00:11:43,871
Those are international waterways.

111
00:11:43,971 --> 00:11:53,822
[Host] They cannot normalize nor can we tolerate them trying to normalize a system in which the Iranians decide who gets to use an international waterway and how much you have to pay them to use it.

112
00:11:56,052 --> 00:11:59,027
[Host] I think I inadvertently called him Vice President Rubio.

113
00:11:59,027 --> 00:12:00,963
He, of course, is the Secretary of State.

114
00:12:00,963 --> 00:12:05,402
What is he forgetting, that the United States is trying to block the Strait of Hormuz as well?

115
00:12:06,163 --> 00:12:07,318
[Guest] Of course.

116
00:12:07,318 --> 00:12:14,694
But I just want to point out that he talked about this new offer that's supposed to be better than previous offers.

117
00:12:14,694 --> 00:12:18,864
As I described it a few minutes ago, the new offer is not better.

118
00:12:19,864 --> 00:12:21,556
[Guest] It's a worse offer.

119
00:12:21,556 --> 00:12:30,082
And what he doesn't understand and the president doesn't understand is that the Iranians are not going to give up control of the Strait.

120
00:12:30,082 --> 00:12:33,154
They'd be crazy to give up control of the Strait.

121
00:12:33,154 --> 00:12:35,599
Not only in the midst of this conflict,

122
00:12:35,700 --> 00:12:40,810
[Guest] but for as far as the eye can see. It is where their leverage comes from.

123
00:12:40,810 --> 00:12:48,950
The control of the Strait plus all those missiles, both cruise missiles, ballistic missiles, and of course drones that they have.

124
00:12:49,350 --> 00:12:53,524
[Guest] They're not going to give those things up. That's their leverage.

125
00:12:53,524 --> 00:12:59,299
And by the way, with regard to Secretary of State Rubio and his absence from the negotiating process.

126
00:13:00,052 --> 00:13:07,372
[Guest] You want to understand that there are two members of the administration who desperately want to become president in 2028.

127
00:13:07,372 --> 00:13:10,096
One is Marco Rubio and the other is J. D. Vance.

128
00:13:10,096 --> 00:13:14,352
And both of them understand that if you get involved in these negotiations,

129
00:13:14,851 --> 00:13:25,076
[Guest] you in the end are going to end up making significant concessions to the Iranians because the Iranians are in the driver's seat here.

130
00:13:25,076 --> 00:13:27,251
We've basically lost this war.

131
00:13:27,700 --> 00:13:36,904
[Guest] And if you make those concessions, if you're the point person for making those concessions, you're going to take a lot of heat from the Israel lobby.

132
00:13:36,904 --> 00:13:42,649
You're going to be in trouble with the lobby and that's going to make it hard to become president.

133
00:13:42,750 --> 00:13:45,786
[Guest] So you can rest assured that J. D.

134
00:13:45,786 --> 00:13:53,450
Vance has no interest in going to Islamabad and being the point man in the negotiations with the Iranians.

135
00:13:53,450 --> 00:13:57,245
[Host] I don't know if he can wash that. That stain off his hands.

136
00:13:57,245 --> 00:14:00,696
I agree with you, but he might be indelibly damaged already.

137
00:14:01,460 --> 00:14:06,059
[Guest] I think that may be true for sure. But I would just say to you,

138
00:14:06,210 --> 00:14:29,409
[Guest] Rubio has done a brilliant job given the fact that he's Secretary of State and National Security Advisor at staying out of these negotiations because he fully understands, I am sure, that he just doesn't want to get involved because in the end we're going to lose the lobby and Israel itself are going to be outraged by any compromises.

139
00:14:29,620 --> 00:14:35,419
[Guest] that we make and whoever actually makes those compromises is going to pay a significant political price.

140
00:14:35,769 --> 00:14:42,669
[Host] From the Iranian perspective, surely they know that they're negotiating with Netanyahu's puppets.

141
00:14:44,244 --> 00:14:47,561
[Guest] Oh, absolutely. They've made that clear.

142
00:14:47,561 --> 00:14:51,362
That's why they want Vance to come to the negotiations.

143
00:14:51,362 --> 00:14:59,793
They know that Kushner is basically an Israeli cutout and that not only is Wittkopf a Zionist, but he's demonstrated quite

144
00:15:00,000 --> 00:15:05,670
[Guest] clearly both in his negotiations with the Iranians and the Russians that he's massively incompetent.

145
00:15:05,670 --> 00:15:09,450
So they don't want to deal with those two. They want to deal with Vance.

146
00:15:09,549 --> 00:15:15,294
[Guest] And they did deal with Vance over the weekend of April 11th, 12th.

147
00:15:15,294 --> 00:15:18,399
That did not work out very well. I mean,

148
00:15:18,450 --> 00:15:27,245
[Guest] what has to happen here is that the United States has to feel more pain and the world has to feel more pain and put pressure on the United States.

149
00:15:27,245 --> 00:15:32,785
to end this as quickly as possible before we're going to get any kind of meaningful negotiations.

150
00:15:34,735 --> 00:15:38,983
[Host] How did Trump lose his war of choosing?

151
00:15:38,983 --> 00:15:49,324
Poor preparation, no articulation of achievable military goals, going too quickly, his hand forced by Netanyahu.

152
00:15:49,324 --> 00:15:50,986
What do you think?

153
00:15:51,625 --> 00:15:56,275
[Guest] He had a strategy that was guaranteed to fail.

154
00:15:57,475 --> 00:16:18,676
[Guest] I mean, the Israelis convinced President Trump that if we and they attacked Iran with a shock and awe campaign and sitting at the center of that shock and awe campaign was a decapitation strategy, that that would cause the regime to collapse.

155
00:16:18,964 --> 00:16:23,542
[Guest] and put in place a new regime that would dance to our tune.

156
00:16:23,542 --> 00:16:28,805
And this would be very easy to do. We would win a quick and decisive victory.

157
00:16:28,805 --> 00:16:30,514
And you want to remember.

158
00:16:31,635 --> 00:16:37,960
[Guest] That virtually all of President Trump's advisors told him that this was ridiculous.

159
00:16:37,960 --> 00:16:42,686
The only possible exception is Pete Hexeth. But as I've said before,

160
00:16:42,836 --> 00:16:46,327
[Guest] Pete Hexeth is not a serious strategist.

161
00:16:46,327 --> 00:16:50,401
And I don't believe even Trump takes him that seriously.

162
00:16:50,401 --> 00:16:59,785
But General Kang, John Ratcliffe, the head of the CIA, Vance himself, and Rubio all said that the strategy that the Israelis had.

163
00:16:59,700 --> 00:17:03,576
[Guest] as it put forward, was not likely to work.

164
00:17:03,576 --> 00:17:17,299
It's a very interesting case because the deep state and the president's principal American advisors warned him against executing the strategy that the Israelis had come up with.

165
00:17:17,400 --> 00:17:28,150
[Guest] But Trump decided for one reason or another that he was going to go along with the Israelis and they executed a strategy and I want to be clear here that was guaranteed to fail.

166
00:17:28,756 --> 00:17:40,979
[Guest] We have no instance in recorded history of an air campaign alone toppling a regime and that leading to a favorable outcome.

167
00:17:40,979 --> 00:17:42,938
It just doesn't work.

168
00:17:42,938 --> 00:17:52,456
You can't use air power alone to create regime change and win a war in a couple days or a week's time.

169
00:17:52,556 --> 00:17:57,092
[Guest] It just doesn't happen. And I think all of his advisors.

170
00:17:57,092 --> 00:18:07,796
understood that but the president allowed himself to be bamboozled by BB Netanyahu and the head of Mossad as well David Barnea who was a key player and

171
00:18:07,796 --> 00:18:08,096
[Guest] I mean,

172
00:18:08,096 --> 00:18:11,996
[Guest] he is paying the price for that I should say we are paying the price

173
00:18:11,996 --> 00:18:12,046
[Host] yes,

174
00:18:12,046 --> 00:18:12,395
[Guest] for that

175
00:18:12,395 --> 00:18:13,498
[Host] we are.

176
00:18:13,498 --> 00:18:21,296
Do you think that his advisors, because of his volcanic personality, extraordinary view of himself.

177
00:18:22,483 --> 00:18:28,388
[Host] intellectual vapidity, refusal to read all these things taken together.

178
00:18:28,388 --> 00:18:36,034
Do you think his advisors are afraid to contradict him to his face or afraid to contradict Netanyahu?

179
00:18:37,364 --> 00:18:39,904
[Guest] Sure, there's just no question about that.

180
00:18:39,904 --> 00:18:45,898
And again, you want to remember that two of the principal advisors of the four that I mentioned are Marco Rubio and J.

181
00:18:45,898 --> 00:18:50,014
D. Vance, and they both want to be president of the United States. And therefore,

182
00:18:50,064 --> 00:18:56,064
[Guest] they want to remain in the good graces of Donald Trump and in the good graces of Israel.

183
00:18:56,064 --> 00:18:58,564
They are in many ways in a straitjacket.

184
00:18:58,564 --> 00:19:01,189
There are just limits to what they can do.

185
00:19:01,189 --> 00:19:04,814
And when President Trump decides he wants to do something,

186
00:19:04,660 --> 00:19:09,194
[Guest] something and Netanyahu is in favor of that same strategy.

187
00:19:09,194 --> 00:19:18,949
There are just real limits to what somebody like Rubio or Vance can do to fight with the president to tell him that this is a really bad idea.

188
00:19:18,949 --> 00:19:21,559
And I think, by the way, General Kane,

189
00:19:21,809 --> 00:19:30,419
[Guest] who many people badmouth, has, in my opinion, behaved admirably here, as best I can tell from what's in the public record.

190
00:19:30,419 --> 00:19:31,809
Cane, who was Trump's

191
00:19:31,923 --> 00:19:44,552
[Guest] handpicked chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff has told Trump at numerous points along the way that we did not have the capability to achieve the goals that he was pursuing, he meaning Donald Trump.

192
00:19:44,552 --> 00:19:45,523
And furthermore,

193
00:19:45,624 --> 00:19:53,925
[Guest] Cain has told them that if we got into a war with Iran, we would run down our inventory of boutique weapons to a very dangerous point.

194
00:19:53,925 --> 00:19:58,601
And of course, that's where we are now. And that's one of the principal reasons.

195
00:19:58,601 --> 00:19:59,887
Reasons we don't want.

196
00:20:00,000 --> 00:20:03,349
[Guest] restart the war. We don't have the weaponry to wage it.

197
00:20:03,349 --> 00:20:07,066
[Host] How dangerous is that point as we speak, Professor Mare Shimer?

198
00:20:07,066 --> 00:20:07,650
Do we know?

199
00:20:07,650 --> 00:20:20,150
[Guest] No, we don't know the details, but we do know that lots and lots of tomahawk missiles have been used, lots and lots of patriot missiles, thad missiles have been used,

200
00:20:20,250 --> 00:20:26,599
[Guest] all sorts of smart smart bombs have been used, and this has serious consequences for

201
00:20:26,771 --> 00:20:54,422
[Guest] containing China and East Asia as you've heard me say on the show before we were supposed to pivot to Asia to contain China but what we're doing is we're pivoting away from China we're bringing all sorts of military forces out of East Asia into the Gulf region because we need all the weapons we can get to fight against Iran and the problem that you face is when you expand these weapons you just can't replace them in a month's time

202
00:20:54,163 --> 00:21:03,144
[Guest] Once time or a year's time, it takes years to produce all the weapons that we've already used up and we don't want to be in a position where we use up more of them.

203
00:21:03,144 --> 00:21:05,963
But the point I'm making to you about General Kane is,

204
00:21:06,013 --> 00:21:12,174
[Guest] unsurprisingly, he recognized this a long time ago and he's advised the president accordingly.

205
00:21:12,174 --> 00:21:17,912
But Trump didn't listen to him because Trump thought he could win a quick and decisive victory.

206
00:21:17,912 --> 00:21:21,114
But once he doesn't win a quick and decisive victory.

207
00:21:21,011 --> 00:21:49,261
[Guest] victory he's in the deep soup and that's where we are today and of course this is why the military is now telling trump don't start this war let me put it differently don't start this bombing campaign up again because it's not going to work and of course if you don't do the bombing campaign and you have no ground forces option which we don't have you're reduced to relying on a naval blockade and then the question is do you think that this naval blockade is going to bring the iranians

208
00:21:49,299 --> 00:22:06,299
[Guest] to their knees all I can say is good luck on that one that's not going to happen either you can inflict huge amounts of punishment on Iranians and they will not throw their hands up they are facing an existential threat and when you're facing an existential threat you fight to the last person

209
00:22:07,700 --> 00:22:16,849
[Host] What will happen if the United States enters into some sort of a long-term peaceful agreement with Iran that excludes Israel?

210
00:22:18,132 --> 00:22:32,082
[Guest] You know, I've thought about this, and I think the connective issue that makes it hard to separate those two dimensions of the problem is Iranian support for Hezbollah and Hamas.

211
00:22:33,031 --> 00:22:41,206
[Guest] The Israelis are going to continue to pound Hezbollah, just to pick on that example, and we see that happening right now.

212
00:22:41,206 --> 00:22:46,338
There's supposed to be a ceasefire, but in fact, there's no ceasefire. Hezbollah.

213
00:22:46,338 --> 00:22:49,000
on the idea for firing away at each other,

214
00:22:49,049 --> 00:22:52,855
[Guest] and that's going to continue for as far as the eye can see.

215
00:22:52,855 --> 00:22:57,683
But the Iranians support Hezbollah, they support Hamas, and they support the Houthis.

216
00:22:57,683 --> 00:23:03,249
And the Iranians, under no circumstances, are going to give up the support for those three groups.

217
00:23:03,849 --> 00:23:15,022
[Guest] That is going to make it very hard for the United States to reach a meaningful peace agreement with Iran because Israel is inextricable.

218
00:23:15,022 --> 00:23:19,289
strictly linked with Iran vis-a-vis those three groups.

219
00:23:19,289 --> 00:23:23,634
And the United States is, of course, linked with Israel.

220
00:23:23,733 --> 00:23:28,683
[Guest] So I think all of this tells you you're not going to get a meaningful peace agreement here.

221
00:23:28,983 --> 00:23:40,993
[Guest] You may get, you know, some Rube Goldberg type agreement that, you know, puts out the fire for a while, but there's no real hope of a meaningful peace agreement.

222
00:23:40,993 --> 00:23:44,902
agreement. And this is in large part because of Israel.

223
00:23:44,951 --> 00:23:53,394
[Guest] As I've argued for a long time, actually with Steve Walt, you have to understand that Israel is a giant albatross around their neck.

224
00:23:53,394 --> 00:23:56,951
I think more and more Americans are coming to realize that.

225
00:23:57,251 --> 00:24:04,025
[Guest] But we are in deep trouble in the Middle East because of Israel, and we have no way of fixing the problem.

226
00:24:04,025 --> 00:24:09,551
The lobby is so powerful here in the United States when it comes to influencing policymakers.

227
00:24:09,748 --> 00:24:36,147
[Guest] makers that it's just hard to make any progress in solving this problem and by the way the principal reason we're not moving towards some sort of ceasefire now some sort of even half-baked agreement is in large part because of Israel in the lobby they just will not let Trump cut any kind of meaningful deal with the Iranians they want the war to go on

228
00:24:36,248 --> 00:24:40,450
[Host] So where will we be in your view? when six months or eight months.

229
00:24:40,900 --> 00:24:50,653
[Guest] Well, we may have, you know, some sort of Rube Goldberg agreement, you know, that allows commerce to flow through the strait.

230
00:24:50,653 --> 00:24:55,786
There may be no blockade. The Iranians will be controlling the strait.

231
00:24:55,786 --> 00:24:59,599
I find it hard to believe that we'll have a nuclear.

232
00:25:00,000 --> 00:25:02,319
[Guest] agreement, I hope were wrong.

233
00:25:02,319 --> 00:25:07,900
But if we do have a nuclear agreement, it's going to look something like the JCPOA, which

234
00:25:07,900 --> 00:25:08,250
[Host] Right.

235
00:25:08,250 --> 00:25:14,063
[Guest] Iran is going to maintain the right and the ability to enrich uranium.

236
00:25:14,063 --> 00:25:17,118
And Israel is never going to accept that.

237
00:25:17,118 --> 00:25:20,099
The lobby is never going to accept that.

238
00:25:20,150 --> 00:25:26,799
[Guest] And the neoconservatives more generally in this country who are very powerful in policy circles are never going to accept.

239
00:25:26,771 --> 00:25:37,947
[Guest] So, you know, we're just going to go on and on arguing with the Iranians about their nuclear capability, threatening them and so forth and so on.

240
00:25:37,947 --> 00:25:43,571
And by the way, if you don't get a meaningful agreement on the nuclear issue,

241
00:25:43,721 --> 00:25:53,729
[Guest] then we're going to run into the possibility that the Israelis may use nuclear weapons against Iran to deal with that problem.

242
00:25:53,729 --> 00:25:55,372
So the future here is.

243
00:25:55,284 --> 00:25:59,967
[Guest] is bleak. And by the way, the future is bleak in Europe as well.

244
00:25:59,967 --> 00:26:02,634
The future in East Asia is bleak as well.

245
00:26:03,034 --> 00:26:06,255
[Guest] We have made a complete hash of things.

246
00:26:06,255 --> 00:26:19,483
Of course, it's not only the result of the Trump administration's policies, although this Iran war has contributed greatly to that, but the whole disaster in Ukraine just goes on and on and on.

247
00:26:19,933 --> 00:26:31,534
[Guest] And that is going to have serious serious negative strategic consequences for as far as the eye can see that, as I pointed out before, are inextricably bound up with what's going on in the Gulf.

248
00:26:31,733 --> 00:26:42,584
[Guest] And then this, you know, leaves aside the whole question of East Asia, which is in many ways the most dangerous area of all because that's where the United States faces a peer competitor.

249
00:26:43,183 --> 00:26:47,227
[Guest] I shudder to think what would happen if we had a crisis in East Asia.

250
00:26:47,227 --> 00:26:51,481
I hope Trump can work with Xi Jinping to make sure that that that doesn't happen.

251
00:26:51,481 --> 00:26:52,793
But you want to remember,

252
00:26:52,943 --> 00:27:02,037
[Guest] we have two major wars taking place, one in the Gulf and the other in Europe, and we don't have a war in East Asia.

253
00:27:02,037 --> 00:27:05,955
But if we did, we would be in the really deep kimchi.

254
00:27:05,955 --> 00:27:10,243
And thankfully, we don't have that problem. And hopefully,

255
00:27:10,394 --> 00:27:15,594
[Guest] President Trump can work something out with Xi so that that doesn't happen.

256
00:27:16,180 --> 00:27:20,691
[Host] What can President Trump work out with President Putin?

257
00:27:20,691 --> 00:27:23,820
I mean, and does Putin have his own issues?

258
00:27:23,820 --> 00:27:32,480
Do you sense impatience on the part of Russian elites, Kremlin officials and average Russians with a four year war now?

259
00:27:33,203 --> 00:27:34,953
[Guest] Yeah, there's no question about that.

260
00:27:35,003 --> 00:27:44,403
[Guest] I've been thinking about the possibility that Russians, the Russians themselves might use nuclear weapons at some point.

261
00:27:44,403 --> 00:27:57,033
It's quite clear that the Europeans are doing everything they can to help the Ukrainians and the Ukrainians are getting quite effective at hitting targets inside of Russia.

262
00:27:57,033 --> 00:28:01,953
And the end result is Russian foreign policy elites and even the...

263
00:28:01,748 --> 00:28:06,590
[Guest] Even the public are getting antsy about settling this war.

264
00:28:06,590 --> 00:28:13,926
They're putting great pressure on President Putin to put an end to it, and it's not easy to do that.

265
00:28:13,926 --> 00:28:18,402
I mean, even as the Russians capture more and more territory,

266
00:28:18,652 --> 00:28:28,503
[Guest] the fact is that the Ukrainians with all these drones and all the help they're getting from Europe and even the United States are able to attack targets in Russia.

267
00:28:28,503 --> 00:28:31,902
And the question is, what will the Russians do in response?

268
00:28:32,102 --> 00:28:41,090
[Guest] And there's this very prominent strategist who I actually know reasonably well, Sergei Karaganov, who has been making the argument for a long time.

269
00:28:41,090 --> 00:28:44,279
long time that the Russians have to put an end to this.

270
00:28:44,380 --> 00:28:50,329
[Guest] And the only way you can do that is to use nuclear weapons, not start a general thermonuclear war,

271
00:28:50,480 --> 00:28:59,439
[Guest] but use nuclear weapons against the West in a demonstrative way to signal to the West that enough is enough.

272
00:28:59,439 --> 00:29:10,329
And if they continue to support Ukraine and allow Ukraine to destroy Russian infrastructure, then what the Russians will do is they'll go up.

273
00:29:10,099 --> 00:29:12,703
[Guest] blow up the nuclear escalation ladder.

274
00:29:12,703 --> 00:29:22,950
And Kara Ganov argues that once you use a few nuclear weapons against the West, they will get the message loudly and clearly, and they will cease and desist from supporting Ukraine.

275
00:29:23,349 --> 00:29:28,849
[Guest] But the key point here is you don't want to put the Russians in a desperate situation.

276
00:29:29,849 --> 00:29:34,132
[Guest] And of course, that's exactly what Europe is trying to do.

277
00:29:34,132 --> 00:29:45,422
As I was saying before, Sergey Lavrov gave a very important very important speech on April 24th, and it would be well worth people's while to go back and look at that speech.

278
00:29:45,571 --> 00:29:56,588
[Guest] But Lavrov makes it very clear that he believes, and of course he's reflecting a Russian perspective on this, that the West has declared war against Russia.

279
00:29:56,588 --> 00:30:00,349
He believes that Russia is at war with Russia. the West.

280
00:30:00,650 --> 00:30:07,067
[Guest] And he believes that Russia's just not fighting Ukraine inside of Ukraine.

281
00:30:07,067 --> 00:30:10,120
Russia is also fighting against Europe.

282
00:30:10,120 --> 00:30:19,356
And he says very clearly that he believes that the Europeans are out to To achieve a strategic victory against Russia.

283
00:30:19,455 --> 00:30:31,655
[Guest] And what he basically is saying is that the Europeans, and of course this means the West in general, and he uses the term the West, wants to knock the Russians out of the ranks of the great powers.

284
00:30:32,655 --> 00:30:45,822
[Guest] And when you are pursuing a goal like that and you're inflicting significant damage on Russian infrastructure, you're going to give the Russians.

285
00:30:45,822 --> 00:30:51,932
significant incentives to get tough and maybe even use nuclear weapons.

286
00:30:53,364 --> 00:30:56,151
[Guest] I didn't think we'd be at this point.

287
00:30:56,151 --> 00:30:59,930
I'm actually quite surprised that I'm saying what I'm saying.

288
00:30:59,930 --> 00:31:06,744
But I think one does not want to underestimate what's going on in Ukraine and how dangerous that situation is.

289
00:31:06,744 --> 00:31:07,363
And again,

290
00:31:07,463 --> 00:31:13,213
[Guest] getting back to the Middle East, I was talking about the possibility that Israel might use nuclear weapons.

291
00:31:13,213 --> 00:31:18,663
I'm not saying that's likely any more than I'm saying that it's likely the Russians will use nuclear weapons.

292
00:31:18,814 --> 00:31:22,179
[Guest] But you do not want to underestimate.

293
00:31:22,179 --> 00:31:26,891
The radical steps that states will take if they feel desperate.

294
00:31:26,891 --> 00:31:37,288
And you can hypothesize plausible situations where both the Israelis and the Russians feel desperate and think about using nuclear weapons.

295
00:31:37,387 --> 00:31:45,331
[Guest] And by the way, you want to understand that if Israel were to use nuclear weapons against Iran, Iran does not have the capability to retaliate.

296
00:31:45,331 --> 00:31:48,488
And if Russia were to use nuclear weapons inside of Ukraine,

297
00:31:48,788 --> 00:31:53,116
[Guest] the Ukrainians can't retaliate. So this is a very dangerous situation.

298
00:31:53,116 --> 00:31:54,447
situation that we're in.

299
00:31:54,447 --> 00:32:02,049
And if you think about our discussion on this show and your discussion with our colleagues and other shows that you have during the week,

300
00:32:02,150 --> 00:32:08,342
[Guest] I think everybody is very pessimistic about where all these conflicts are headed.

301
00:32:08,342 --> 00:32:14,395
Nobody, you know, among us can tell a happy story about how any of these conflicts end.

302
00:32:14,395 --> 00:32:18,500
And this, I think, should make all of us extremely worried.

303
00:32:19,539 --> 00:32:24,496
[Host] And worried we are. Professor Mearsheimer, thank you very much.

304
00:32:24,496 --> 00:32:30,162
Thanks for that extraordinary analysis on both counts, on both Iran and Ukraine.

305
00:32:30,162 --> 00:32:34,339
We'll look forward to seeing you next week, my dear friend.

306
00:32:34,690 --> 00:32:36,589
[Guest] I look forward to it as well, Judge.

307
00:32:36,890 --> 00:32:38,113
[Host] Thank you.

308
00:32:38,113 --> 00:32:45,240
Coming up later today at one o'clock on all of this, the golden boy, Max Blumenthal at two o'clock.

309
00:32:45,715 --> 00:32:50,713
[Host] Maco, are American troops willing to kill innocents knowingly?

310
00:32:50,713 --> 00:32:57,448
And at three o'clock, Colonel Karen Kwiatkowski writes a fascinating piece up at Judge Knapp.

311
00:32:57,448 --> 00:33:01,286
Are we on the abyss? Are we on a cliff of the insane?

312
00:33:01,286 --> 00:33:03,965
Judge Napolitano for judging freedom.

